Project 1:¶

Visual Narratives With Code¶

Dataset:¶

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/yashdevladdha/uber-ride-analytics-dashboard

I chose this dataset because it seemed interesting and it was the first one I came across.

Dataset Size: 150,000 rows and 22 columns.

Columns:

Date - Date of the booking
Time - Time of the booking
Booking ID - Unique identifier for each ride booking
Booking Status - Status of booking (Completed, Cancelled by Customer, Cancelled by Driver, etc.)
Customer ID - Unique identifier for customers
Vehicle Type - Type of vehicle (Go Mini, Go Sedan, Auto, eBike/Bike, UberXL, Premier Sedan)
Pickup Location - Starting location of the ride
Drop Location - Destination location of the ride
Avg VTAT - Average time for driver to reach pickup location (in minutes)
Avg CTAT - Average trip duration from pickup to destination (in minutes)
Cancelled Rides by Customer - Customer-initiated cancellation flag
Reason for cancelling by Customer - Reason for customer cancellation
Cancelled Rides by Driver - Driver-initiated cancellation flag
Driver Cancellation Reason - Reason for driver cancellation
Incomplete Rides - Incomplete ride flag
Incomplete Rides Reason - Reason for incomplete rides
Booking Value - Total fare amount for the ride
Ride Distance - Distance covered during the ride (in km)
Driver Ratings - Rating given to driver (1-5 scale)
Customer Rating - Rating given by customer (1-5 scale)
Payment Method - Method used for payment (UPI, Cash, Credit Card, Uber Wallet, Debit Card)

Standard Python libraries for data visualization.

Preprocessing¶

First step of my preprocessing I wanted to focus on a specific subset of variables and decided on: Booking Status, Vehicle Type, Reason for cancelling by Customer, Cancelled Rides by Driver, Driver Cancellation Reason, Incomplete Rides Reason, Customer Rating. I am also looking at some of these variables in relation to time and date. There are a lot of missing values in this dataset but not in the way that it would take away from the meaning of the visualizations and all of the visuals automatically drop NAN values. A lot of the missing values are caused by values not being provided to Uber from the driver or customer.

Time Analysis¶

Rides separated by Booking Status¶

In the first visualization I want to look at is when during the day the most rides were scheduled. The visualization shows a peak at around 10:20 and 18:40 since this variable was tracked using a 24-hour clock. This is equivalent to 10:20AM and 6:40PM on the 12-hour clock. We see that the other Booking Statuses follow a similar peak pattern.

In [5]:
status_colors = {
    "Total": "brown",
    "Completed": "green",
    "Cancelled by Customer": "blue",
    "Cancelled by Driver": "orange",
    "Incomplete": "red",
    "No Driver Found": "#A219E1"
}

# Convert Time column to datetime
df["Time"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Time"], format="%H:%M:%S", errors="coerce")

# Round down to nearest 20 minutes
df["Time_20min"] = df["Time"].dt.floor("20min").dt.strftime("%H:%M")

# Count rides by 20-min interval and Booking Status
status_counts = df.groupby(["Time_20min", "Booking Status"]).size().reset_index(name="Number of Rides")

# Also calculate total rides regardless of status
total_counts = df.groupby("Time_20min").size().reset_index(name="Number of Rides")
total_counts["Booking Status"] = "Total"  # Add label so we can plot it together

# Combine into one DataFrame
plot_df = pd.concat([status_counts, total_counts])

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(14,6))
sns.lineplot(data=plot_df, x="Time_20min", y="Number of Rides", hue="Booking Status", palette=status_colors, marker="o")

plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.title("Number of Rides Scheduled (20-Minute Intervals, by Booking Status)")
plt.xlabel("Time of Day (20-min bins)")
plt.ylabel("Number of Rides")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Separated by Booking Status with a focus on cancelled/incomplete rides¶

For this visualization I wanted to focus on the lower portion of the above visual

In [6]:
# Define the statuses we care about
problem_statuses = ["Cancelled by Customer", "Cancelled by Driver", "Incomplete", "No Driver Found"]

# Filter dataset
problem_df = df[df["Booking Status"].isin(problem_statuses)]

# Count rides by 20-min interval and Booking Status
problem_counts = (
    problem_df.groupby(["Time_20min", "Booking Status"])
    .size()
    .reset_index(name="Number of Rides")
)

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(14,6))
sns.lineplot(
    data=problem_counts,
    x="Time_20min",
    y="Number of Rides",
    hue="Booking Status",
    palette=status_colors,
    marker="o"
)

plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.title("Problematic Rides (Cancelled, Incomplete, No Driver Found) by 20-Minute Intervals")
plt.xlabel("Time of Day (20-min bins)")
plt.ylabel("Number of Rides")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Customer Rating¶

The first visual under this section looks at the distribution of customer ratings as a histogram. The next 4 look at the average customer rating across the year split into quarters. There is also a line showing the max, min, and average rating for each quarter.

In [12]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))

# Create evenly spaced bins between min and max
bin_edges = np.linspace(df["Customer Rating"].min(), df["Customer Rating"].max(), 11)

sns.histplot(
    df["Customer Rating"].dropna(), 
    bins=bin_edges, 
    color="skyblue", 
    edgecolor="black"
)

plt.title("Distribution of Customer Ratings")
plt.xlabel("Customer Rating")
plt.ylabel("Number of Rides")
plt.xticks(bin_edges, rotation=0)
plt.show()
In [13]:
ratings_over_time = df.groupby("Date")["Customer Rating"].mean().reset_index()

# Determine split points
n = len(ratings_over_time)
q1 = n // 4
q2 = n // 2
q3 = 3 * n // 4

# Create 4 subplots (stacked vertically)
fig, axes = plt.subplots(4, 1, figsize=(15, 20), sharey=True)

quarters = [
    ratings_over_time.iloc[:q1],
    ratings_over_time.iloc[q1:q2],
    ratings_over_time.iloc[q2:q3],
    ratings_over_time.iloc[q3:]
]

titles = [
    "Average Customer Rating (1st Quarter of Dates)",
    "Average Customer Rating (2nd Quarter of Dates)",
    "Average Customer Rating (3rd Quarter of Dates)",
    "Average Customer Rating (4th Quarter of Dates)"
]

# Plot each quarter
for i, (data, title) in enumerate(zip(quarters, titles)):
    sns.lineplot(data=data, x="Date", y="Customer Rating",
                 marker="o", color="green", ax=axes[i])
    
    # Get min, max, mean for this quarter
    y_min = data["Customer Rating"].min()
    y_max = data["Customer Rating"].max()
    y_mean = data["Customer Rating"].mean()
    
    # Add reference lines
    axes[i].axhline(y=y_min, color="red", linestyle="--", label=f"Min: {y_min:.2f}")
    axes[i].axhline(y=y_max, color="blue", linestyle="--", label=f"Max: {y_max:.2f}")
    axes[i].axhline(y=y_mean, color="orange", linestyle="--", label=f"Avg: {y_mean:.2f}")
    
    # Titles & labels
    axes[i].set_title(title)
    axes[i].set_ylabel("Average Rating")
    axes[i].tick_params(axis="x", rotation=90)
    if i < 3:
        axes[i].set_xlabel("")
    else:
        axes[i].set_xlabel("Date")
    
    axes[i].legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Reflection:¶

I feel like I made the best visual choice for each area I wanted to cover even with the amount of null values in the dataset. Something I would change is maybe make more time based visualizations and if the project called for it I would like to have taken a more machine learning based analysis into the dataset.
